{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ac78a3fd-324f-495a-83d1-880380d994b9","content":"## What happened\n\nStarting in **.NET 7**, Microsoft began removing platform-native DSA support on macOS because **Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) dropped DSA entirely**. The `DSA.Create()` call now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. On Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG), it still works.\n\nIf your .NET 10 builds appeared to work, you may have been relying on a compatibility shim or OpenSSL-backed path that was fully removed in .NET 11.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify legacy signatures**, the cleanest fix is to use **BouncyCastle**, which is a fully managed implementation with no platform crypto dependency:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the platform DSA call:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, byte[] publicKeyDer)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);\n    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\"); // match your original hash\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n## Long-term recommendation\n\nDSA is considered **legacy** — migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** for new signatures and keep BouncyCastle only for verifying old ones during a transition period.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"49af49ed-f71e-492a-8ef8-ea66da22ea71","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nLet me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7, Microsoft made DSA.Create() throw a PlatformNotSupportedException on macOS. This is because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. On Linux, DSA is still supported through OpenSSL, and on Windows through CNG/CAPI. But on macOS, since Apple removed DSA support from their crypto libraries, .NET can't provide a native implementation.\n \nWait, I need to reconsider the timeline here. The user mentioned upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11 in April 2026, but the DSA breaking change on macOS was introduced back in .NET 7. If it's working on .NET 10 but failing on .NET 11, something else might be going on—perhaps a more recent change or a different aspect of the DSA implementation that changed between those versions. The real problem is that Apple's cryptographic frameworks don't support DSA anymore, so .NET on macOS has to throw an exception when you try to use it. I can suggest a few workarounds: BouncyCastle provides its own managed DSA implementation that works cross-platform, you could try using OpenSSL through P/Invoke though that's messier, or ideally migrate away from DSA since it's outdated anyway.\n\nFor legacy signatures that still need DSA verification, BouncyCastle is the practical solution during a transition period while you move new code to ECDSA or EdDSA. The timing here is interesting—Microsoft marked DSA as obsolete in .NET 7 and it throws on macOS, but the user is seeing it work in .NET 10 and fail in .NET 11, which suggests there might have been a further tightening of the restrictions in the latest version.","outputTokens":1492,"requestId":"1433:1B9BC9:E4FB1A7:FE8C552:69EC1B0B"},"id":"7d91cb0a-5b94-4247-aac6-f0277374f5f1","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:38:50.607Z","parentId":"ce4f572f-13da-4469-86b1-e2cd9e8f0f0b"}
